Differing Strategies to Meet Information-Sharing Needs: Publicly ConclusionsBoth community and enterprise HIEs support aggregating clinical data and following patients across settings.
Although they can be complementary, community and enterprise HIEs nonetheless compete for providers' attention and organizational resources.
Health policymakers might try to encourage the type of widespread information exchange pursued by community HIEs, but the business case for enterprise HIEs clearly is stronger.
The sustainability of a community HIE, potentially a public good, may necessitate ongoing public funding and supportive regulation.
